\description{
Build the symmetric adjacency matrix that \code{\link[=spatial]{spatial()}} and \code{\link[=spatial_car]{spatial_car()}}
consume, from a common spatial layout, instead of hand-coding it. The model
still receives an explicit graph (\code{spatial(graph = g$adjacency, ...)}), so the
graph stays inspectable before fitting -- the engine never guesses
connectivity from coordinates silently.

\code{adjacency()} is a single front-door verb that dispatches on the kind of
input:
\describe{
\item{a \code{data.frame}}{cell centroids on a regular grid -- queen (edge or
corner) or rook (edge only) contiguity over the lattice. This covers both
plain coordinate grids and rasterised cells passed as a table of
centres.}
\item{an \code{sf} object}{polygon contiguity from shared boundaries (queen =
share a point or edge; rook = share an edge). Requires \pkg{sf}.}
\item{a \code{SpatRaster} (\pkg{terra}) or \code{stars} object}{raster cells -- the
lattice of (non-\code{NA}) cell centres, queen or rook. Requires \pkg{terra}
or \pkg{stars} respectively.}
}

The result is a \code{tulpa_adjacency} object holding the matrix plus the cell
identifier for each node, so a model can pass \code{g$adjacency} while the
observation data is remapped to 1-based node indices with \code{\link[=node_index]{node_index()}}.
}
